out_desc_tool: he subjects were given the Peabody Picture Vocabulary Test (Dunn, 1965), a wide ly used verbal intelligence test. The subjects' mental age scores were used as the unit of analysis. Form A was used on the pretest, Form B on the immediate posttest, and Form A on the delayed posttest. An alternate form reliability coefficient of .84 was reported in the PPVT manual.

out_desc_tool: All three mathematical tasks were z-standardised and their average then used as comprehensive math score. The reliability of this score was acceptable to good (Cronbach’s αt1/t2 = .81/.77). All subtests had been used in previous research (see, for example, Niklas, Cohrssen, and Tayler 2016  Niklas and Schneider 2014) and are good predictors of children later mathematical abilities in school.

out_desc_tool: The Visual Perception Aspects Test, developed by Sylvia Clutten in South Africa in 2009, was used to measure visuospatial skills in this study. nine visual perceptual aspects are as follows  VD, visual form constancy, VM, VSM, visual– spatial relationships, position-in-space, visual closure, visual figure-ground, and visual analysis and synthesis. Only three of these visuospatial perception aspects were considered in this study

The mathematical language task includes 16 items assessing comparative language (e.g., more, less) and spatial language (e.g., near, far  Purpura & Logan, 2015). All items were designed to be completed without exact quantita- tive skills and in a non-mathematics context.
